<emphasis bold="true" box="[543,600,1943,1964]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[543,600,1943,1964]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, P3: pereiopod 3, P5: pereiopod 5, U: pleotelson and right uropod; scale bars: 100 µm (P3, P5) and 200 µm (U).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Pereiopod 1 (
<figureCitation box="[345,427,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURE 36" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1982,2005]" captionTargetBox="[179,1369,200,1940]" captionTargetId="figure-49@49.[179,1403,193,1948]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 36. Leucon (M.) weigmanni sp. n., A1: antenna 1, Mxp2: maxilliped 2, Mxp3: maxilliped 3, P1: pereiopod 1, P2: pereiopod 2; scale bars: 100 µm (A1, Mxp2, Mxp3) and 200 µm (P1, P2)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246223" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246223/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
, P 
<figureCitation box="[459,470,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1939,1962]" captionTargetBox="[163,1436,1342,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-455@6.[156,1441,1340,1894]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 1. Leucon (A.) polarsterni Ledoyer, 1993, subadult female habitus, 5.5 mm long." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246153/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">1</figureCitation>
): B/R ratio 0.2, relative length of articles I to D: 7/15/30/36/13; basis with two setulate and two hair-like setae; ischium with one setulate at outer distal and one hair-like seta at inner distal corner; merus with one long setulate seta at outer distal corner; carpus with few hair-like setae along margins, distally with two setulate setae; propodus with four setulate setae: one at the proximal outer and one at the distal inner margin, two along the inner and outer margins, two hair-like setae in a short distance to the setulate seta at the inner margin; dactylus with three simple setae along distal inner margin, terminal seta longer than dactylus, two simple setae subterminally; exopod present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Pereiopod 2 (
<figureCitation box="[347,430,404,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 36" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1982,2005]" captionTargetBox="[179,1369,200,1940]" captionTargetId="figure-49@49.[179,1403,193,1948]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 36. Leucon (M.) weigmanni sp. n., A1: antenna 1, Mxp2: maxilliped 2, Mxp3: maxilliped 3, P1: pereiopod 1, P2: pereiopod 2; scale bars: 100 µm (A1, Mxp2, Mxp3) and 200 µm (P1, P2)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246223" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246223/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
, P 
<figureCitation box="[460,475,404,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1980,2003]" captionTargetBox="[152,1415,200,1915]" captionTargetId="figure-49@7.[151,1436,193,1959]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Leucon (A.) polarsterni Ledoyer, 1993, A1: antenna 1, Mxp2: maxilliped 2, Mxp3: maxilliped 3, P1: pereiopod 1, P2: pereiopod 2; scale bars 100 µm (A1, Mxp2, Mxp3) and 200 µm (P1, P2)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246155/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">2</figureCitation>
): B/R ratio 0.6, relative length of articles I to D: 2/14/50/14/21; basis with three setulate setae along inner margin; ischium hardly detectable; merus with one setulate seta at outer margin; carpus with two setulate setae along outer margin, one setulate and one hair-like seta along inner margin, two longer simple setae at distal margin; dactylus with five simple setae at distal margin, longer than dactylus, two shorter simple setae along inner and outer margins; exopod present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Pereiopod 3 (
<figureCitation box="[346,428,583,607]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="50.[151,250,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[227,1318,195,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-49@50.[227,1361,193,1958]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURE 37. Leucon (M.) weigmanni sp. n., P3: pereiopod 3, P5: pereiopod 5, U: pleotelson and right uropod; scale bars: 100 µm (P3, P5) and 200 µm (U)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246225/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
, P 
<figureCitation box="[459,473,583,607]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1961,1984]" captionTargetBox="[183,1413,197,1929]" captionTargetId="figure-51@8.[181,1413,193,1950]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leucon (A.) polarsterni Ledoyer, 1993, P3: pereiopod 3, P4: pereiopod 4, P5: pereiopod 5, U: pleotelson and uropods; scale bars 100 µm (P3, P4, P5) and 200 µm (U)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246159/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">3</figureCitation>
): B/R ratio 1.4, relative length of articles I to D: 12/33/28/19/7; ischium with long setulate seta at inner distal corner; merus with one micro-setulate and one short simple seta at inner margin; carpus with one long simple seta at outer proximal margin, two long simple setae at outer distal corner; propodus with long simple seta at outer distal corner; dactylus with terminal seta (broken off) and two fine setae subterminally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,1256]" box="[197,592,727,751]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Pereiopod 4: damaged, not figured.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Pereiopod 5 (
<figureCitation box="[348,432,764,788]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="50.[151,250,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[227,1318,195,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-49@50.[227,1361,193,1958]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURE 37. Leucon (M.) weigmanni sp. n., P3: pereiopod 3, P5: pereiopod 5, U: pleotelson and right uropod; scale bars: 100 µm (P3, P5) and 200 µm (U)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246225/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
, P 
<figureCitation box="[464,479,764,788]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1765,1788]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,1406,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-448@10.[151,1436,1406,1701]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Leucon (C.) antarcticus Zimmer, 1907, non-ovigerous female habitus, 3.5 mm long." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246163" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246163/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">5</figureCitation>
): Length proportions not given due to artefact of curvature; long simple setae at carpus and propodus distal parts; dactylus with terminal seta (broken off) and two fine setae subterminally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Uropod (
<figureCitation box="[303,390,836,860]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="50.[151,250,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[227,1318,195,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-49@50.[227,1361,193,1958]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURE 37. Leucon (M.) weigmanni sp. n., P3: pereiopod 3, P5: pereiopod 5, U: pleotelson and right uropod; scale bars: 100 µm (P3, P5) and 200 µm (U)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246225/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
, U): Peduncle shorter than rami, three stout cuspidate setae along inner margin; exopod slightly longer than endopod; endopod bi-articulated, basal article 1.8 times as long as distal article, seven strong cuspidate setae along inner margin; distal article with two strong cuspidate setae along inner margin; terminal seta short and stout, long simple seta subterminally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,980,1004]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mühlenhardt-Siegel" authorityYear="2011" box="[525,799,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weigmanni" subGenus="Macrauloleucon">
<emphasis box="[525,799,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Leucon (M.) weigmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ledoyer, 1993" authorityName="Ledoyer" authorityYear="1993" box="[956,1376,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weddelli" subGenus="Macrauloleucon">
<emphasis box="[956,1202,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Leucon (M.) weddelli</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ledoyer, M." box="[1212,1376,980,1004]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="1041 - 1096" refId="ref27331" refString="Ledoyer, M. (1993) Cumacea (Crustacea) de la campagne EPOS 3 du RV Polarstern en mer de Weddell, Antarctique. Journal of Natural History, 27, 1041 - 1096." type="journal article" year="1993">Ledoyer, 1993</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
with respect to the short serration of the dorsomedian line of the carapace and the teeth at the lateral sides of the carapace. However, in the new species there are up to twelve tiny teeth on the carapace side (seven in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ledoyer" authorityYear="1993" box="[1254,1379,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weddelli">
<emphasis box="[1254,1379,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">L. weddelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and three to eight at the dorsomedian line (two in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ledoyer" authorityYear="1993" box="[687,814,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weddelli">
<emphasis box="[687,814,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">L. weddelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The new species has two tiny teeth on the pseudorostrum, which is not armed in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ledoyer" authorityYear="1993" box="[490,614,1124,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weddelli">
<emphasis box="[490,614,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">L. weddelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ledoyer" authorityYear="1993" box="[627,751,1124,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weddelli">
<emphasis box="[627,751,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">L. weddelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has tiny teeth at the posterior margin of the free thoracic segments, which are mostly not present in the new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
The new species is also similar to the species 
<taxonomicName authority="Mühlenhardt-Siegel, 2011" authorityName="Mühlenhardt-Siegel" authorityYear="2011" box="[727,934,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="complexus" status="sp. n." subGenus="Macrauloleucon">
<emphasis box="[727,934,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">L. (M.) complexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[943,1008,1196,1220]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[943,1008,1196,1220]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(described in the following), but this species does have ventral teeth along the pseudorostrum, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Mühlenhardt-Siegel, 2011" authorityName="Mühlenhardt-Siegel" authorityYear="2011" box="[841,1050,1232,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weigmanni" status="sp. n." subGenus="Macrauloleucon">
<emphasis box="[841,1050,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">L. (M.) weigmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1057,1120,1232,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1057,1120,1232,1256]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
does not.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,775,1303,1328]" box="[151,775,1303,1328]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
The number of teeth varies in 
<taxonomicName authority="Mühlenhardt-Siegel, 2011" authorityName="Mühlenhardt-Siegel" authorityYear="2011" box="[488,697,1304,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Leucon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weigmanni" status="sp. n." subGenus="Macrauloleucon">
<emphasis box="[488,697,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">L. (M.) weigmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[704,767,1304,1328]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[704,767,1304,1328]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,1375,1796]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
● in the dorsomedian line of the carapace: Peninsula and western Weddell Sea: 3 (young) - 8 (ovigerous and non-ovigerous) in females, 
<quantity box="[1266,1338,1412,1436]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.905" metricValueMax="2.286" metricValueMin="1.524" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" unit="in" value="7.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="6.0">6–9 in</quantity>
